  "summary": "Geraldine Mary Alexandrina Brown recounts her observations of a murder to Colin Lamb. She describes seeing a beautiful young woman named Sheila Weber run out of a house screaming and grabbing a man who resembled Lamb. This man then entered the house occupied by Miss Pemukh (also referred to as Miss Pembroke). Geraldine notes that a neighbor from number 18, Miss Paxtaville, observed the scene from her steps. Following the incident, the man made a call from a roadside phone booth, and police arrived to remove a dead person in an ambulance. The apartment caretaker, Harry, informed Geraldine that the victim was a man named Mr. Corry. Geraldine also mentions a separate murder case that occurred later at a phone booth.\n\nWhen questioned about the victim's arrival, Geraldine believes Mr. Corry was in the house all along, as she did not see him enter through the front door or garden. She describes the victim as an elderly man, approximately sixty years old, with a trimmed beard and a dark grey suit. Geraldine provides a detailed timeline of the day, noting that Miss Pembroke left around ten o'clock and the housekeeper, Mrs. Crab, left around noon. Geraldine explains that her high level of observation was prompted by an argument with the cook, Ingrid, which led her to watch the street through her telescope. Additionally, Geraldine notes that instead of the usual Southdowns Laundry, a new service called Snowflake Laundry delivered clothes that day.",
